categories of modern politics, from the democratic theory of the division of powers to the strategic doctrine of collateral damage, from the invisible hand of Smith's liberalism to ideas of order and security. But the greatest novelty to emerge from The Kingdom and the Glory is that modern power is not only government but also glory, and that the ceremonial, liturgical, and acclamatory aspects that we have regarded as vestiges of the past actually constitute the basis of Western power. Through a fascinating analysis of liturgical acclamations and ceremonial symbols of power-the throne, the crown, purple cloth, the Fasces, and more-Agamben develops an original genealogy that illuminates the startling function of consent and of the media in modern democracies. With this book, the work begun with Homo Sacer reaches a decisive point, profoundly challenging and renewing our vision of politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aPower (Philosophy). 0aReligion and politics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aChiesa, Lorenzo1 aMandarini, Matteo08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478166440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804781664423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804781664.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles